HEADWORD: Retortion
<hw>Re*tor"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧torsion</ets>. See <er>Retort</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Act of retorting or throwing back;
reflection or turning back.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>retorsion</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was, however, necessary to possess some single term expressive
of this intellectual <qex>retortion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Retaliation.</def>
<rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retortive</ent>⟦br⟧
